description:
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Consultant in Vascular Surgery&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Duration: Substantive &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We are looking to appoint a dynamic, highly motivated vascular surgeon.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The post will be based at St George’s Universities NHS Trust, but will also provide vascular service for St Helier Hospital as a spoke site. Duties at St Helier Hospital will include clinics, ward rounds, with potential for the development of a day surgery list.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There will be a requirement to undertake clinical work on-call and out-of-hours. The new incumbent will be expected to participate in the existing vascular programmes. This job is for ten (10) Programmed Activities. The on-call rota is well established and is run on a 1:9 basis to cover the needs of vascular emergencies.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Vascular Surgery clinical service is provided by a group of vascular surgeons who provide a 24 hour consultant led emergency service for the South West Thames Vascular Network. The managed network encompasses the following Hospitals: St George’s, Kingston, St Helier, Epsom, Croydon, Ashford &amp; St Peter’s and East Surrey.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The St George’s Vascular Institute (SGVI) encompasses an incorporated clinical, research and educational facility on the St George’s site. There is an integrated programme of education, research and clinical services designed to encompass all facets of vascular disease. The successful applicant will be part of a team of vascular consultants who cover aortic disease, endovascular treatments, lower limb disorders, and all aspects of general vascular disease. St George’s is equipped with a state of the art hybrid operating theatre, an experienced vascular laboratory and supported by a motivated team of vascular nurse specialists.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As St George’s is a teaching hospital, the Consultant would be expected to deliver teaching to undergraduate and postgraduate students whilst undertaking DCC duties. Opportunities are available to become involved in audit, clinical research, formal education and educational supervision, if desired, with review of the job plan as appropriate.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The successful candidate would ideally offer competencies to widen the unit’s existing expertise, whilst the trust will grant time, and encourage participation in activities relating to continuing professional development (CPD). Support and education regarding appraisal and revalidation will be given to the successful candidate.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There will also be the opportunities to develop the post holder’s own area of clinical interest alongside the duties described above.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
